Caliber	7.62x51mm NATO (.308 Win) 
Length	46.0"
Weight	11 lbs with  optics
Barrel Length	26 inches 
Stock	 Greyed laminated wood

The Ruger M77 MkII VLE is Ruger's little known Law Enforcement tactical rifle. The rifle is based off of the M77 MkII VT target/varmint rifle but has a few changes. All the metal work is a flat black finish vs. the flat grey color of the VT rifles. 

The VT and VLE rifles have a laminated stock which is nicely contoured with a very wide forearm. The stock is different in that it is composed of darker grey colored laminates, vs the brown colors of the VT. 

The barrel is not as heavy as most tactical rifles, which keeps weight down a little. 

The trigger is a 2 stage trigger, which I personally prefer. 

This VLE has a Redfield 3x9 Battlezone TAC-MOA scope mounted and a MidwayUSA cheek pad.

Will trade I prefer Springfield 1911's but open to other deals

title: For Sale:  18" AR-15 w/ Rifle-length Gas and Battlecomp
postcontent:
Bills are forcing me to sell my ultra-soft shooting and flawlessly reliable 18" AR-15. What makes it recoilless is the rifle-length gas system combined with the battlecomp 1.0 muzzle device. With this setup you can actually get the gun recoiling DOWN if you shoot fast enough. 

It is immensely controllable and has been put to good use, surviving a training class flawlessly without a single stoppage for any reason. 

The rifle's Palmetto State Armory lower is built with a White Oak Armament lower parts kit and includes their ALG trigger. The stock is a Magpul ACS, grip and trigger guard are also Magpul. The barrel is a Green Mountain 18" made of 416R stainless steel and has a 1:7 twist (Green Mountain namelessly makes the barrels used in many top quality AR makers), with a Wilson Combat low-profile gas block. It runs a M16 BCG and the long handguard is a Troy VTAC. 

It also comes with ARMS backup flipup sights already installed and zeroed for 50 yards.

As you can see (or Google), the parts are all top-shelf and it shows. It shoots like a dream and the weight distribution makes it incredibly maneuverable. There is some wear on the left side of the lower from my belt buckle as it swung on me while slung, and there is some scratching on the bottom of the handguard from resting on different real-life barricades like car hoods and boulders. Obviously none of these minor cosmetic blemishes will impede function in any way and if I had planned on selling it then I would've taken better care of its aesthetics. I meant to keep this as my One Rifle but real life has intervened as it always does.

I will also include two metal high-quality D&H 30-round magazines with the rifle. 

Price is $1,250; cash only, no trades and will only sell to an Alabama resident with valid ID. I don't think you'll ever find this nice of a rifle at this low of a price on Armslist ever again. This is not some backyard special going for panic pricing; this is my go-to rifle, made up of top-shelf components, built to perform and to last.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1937 Walther PP Set - Matching slide, frame, with holster - Crown N Proof
postcontent:
I've had a lot of offers, but several tire kickers and flakes.  Prefer Face-to-Face transaction.

I have a 1937 Walther PP .32 cal that sits in my safe and needs a great home.  This gun is a collector's item or can be carried.  It's in beautiful shape, the smoothest slide action I've seen on any Walther (mainly because this one is German made).

The serial number dates back to 1937 (Pre-war) gun and was issued to an officer in the Finance Ministry.  Carries the Crown N proof on the barrel, slide and frame.  Bares R.F.V. 9992 W on the frame, "Reichsfinanzverwaltung” (Reich Finance Administration). This organization was the Nazi equivalent of the United States IRS.

The gun is in good condition.  Mechanically everything works great. The bore is shiny, but the bluing is worn near the muzzle and on parts of the slide from holster wear.

I bought this from a guy who's grandfather brought it back from his time in Europe during WWII.  The holster is original tan leather in fantastic condition.

I took this to the range, shot 1/2 box of .32 through it and it was perfect.  Low recoil, accurate as can be.  It comes with metal finger-grip magazine as well, however I'd recommend a new magazine if you're going to use this as a carry piece.

Price: $900
Prefer Face-to-Face

title: For Sale:  H&A Safety Police - 6 shot - Rare 6" long barrel
postcontent:
Rare and collectible top break, six shot revolver with 6 inch barrel chambered in .32 S&W. It shoots great without fault. Most of these revolvers where short 3" or 3 1/2" barrels. Rare to fine one with a 6 inch barrel. 

A bit of history on this gun. The Safety Police Model was introduced in 1908 and produced until 1917. This gun is marked with that name and the patent date august 21, 1906.

H&A's 1910 catalog H&A stated that the "safety police model" was safe with smokeless powder by making the statement "-----923 rounds of smokeless powder cartridges were fired from one revolver------" The first of it's kind.

title: For Sale:  LaRue Tactical Scope Mount QD LT745
postcontent:
The LT745 places the centerline of the optic 1.5" above the top of the rail for optimum cheek weld with a variety of flat top rifles. The cantilever positions the scope out front over any handguard or barrel nut, eliminating the need to span from the receiver to the handguard. The cantilever also allows the shooter to obtain proper eye relief.

The popularity of the SPR series of mounts is partially due to the innovative backbone that connects the split vertical rings. This design provides a more robust platform for the optics, increases repeatability, and eliminates the need for time-consuming lapping. The rings are precision-machined with the tightest tolerances, and feature threaded steel inserts, built to withstand a lifetime of abuse.

Like all LaRue mounts, it is precision-machined out of bar-stock aluminum and anodized. The locking LaRue Speed Levers provide outstanding return to zero; the optic can be removed, and replaced, without loss of zero. Guaranteed.

20moa built in.
